<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870205-0007 </DOCNO><HL> What's News --Business and Finance</HL><DD> 02/05/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   THE U.S. IS STUDYING evidence that Michael Milken, the head of Drexel Burnham Lambert's junk-bond operations, was a key official in the suspected scheme with Ivan Boesky to profit from corporate takeovers, sources said. The roles of at least four other officials at the investment banking firm also are being studied.    ---   Car sales plummeted 26% in late January despite new incentive programs, leading analysts to conclude that more production cuts are likely. Sales for the month tumbled 33% to the lowest level in four years.    ---   Stock prices rallied broadly in heavy trading. The Dow Jones industrials rose 22.78 points, to a record 2191.23, though the broader averages posted bigger gains. Bonds wound up little changed, while the dollar climbed in cautious trading.    ---   T. Boone Pickens proposed to buy Diamond Shamrock for about $2 billion, his third bid for the energy firm. The move came after Diamond Shamrock unveiled a big restructuring to thwart a Pickens takeover.    ---   American Home Products offered to rescue A.H. Robins from Chapter 11 proceedings by acquiring the health-products maker and assuming its Dalkon Shield liabilities. The minimum price may be $1.03 billion.    ---   Acting antitrust chief Charles Rule is expected to be named permanent head of the Justice Department division, officials said. Rule is an outspoken advocate of deregulation.    ---   USX Corp. plans to cut its steelmaking capacity about 27%, less than the industry had expected. The company, which just settled a long strike, expects to regain its 17% share of the U.S. market by the third quarter.    ---   Senate Finance Chairman Bentsen promised quick action to narrow an estate-tax loophole created by last year's tax law. The move could save the government up to $20 billion in revenue over the next five years.    ---   Pan Am's unions said they would seek another airline to acquire the carrier. They also plan to offer the purchaser a cost-saving proposal that Pan Am's directors rejected.    ---   FCC Commissioner Dennis Patrick soon will be appointed to head the agency, sources said. Patrick is an ardent supporter of deregulation.    ---   Major bond brokers and dealers face growing pressure to broaden access to pricing information on U.S. government securities. Many vow to fight any proposed changes.    ---   General Motors' EDS unit posted a 25% rise in quarterly profit, while its Hughes unit had a 20% decline.    ---   The Farm Credit System may need a federal bailout sooner than expected despite accounting changes adopted last fall to help keep the nation's big farm lender solvent.    ---   Sears Roebuck's profit fell 1.7% in the fourth quarter as merchandise group earnings slid 7%. The results were below analysts' estimates.    ---   Federally insured thrifts had $2.1 billion more in withdrawals than deposits in December, the Bank Board said. Thrift mortgage loans surged 35% last year to a record level.    ---   TRW Inc. announced a 2-for-1 stock split and forecast &quot;double-digit&quot; per-share profit growth 1987.    ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 222,430,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials 2191.23, up 22.78; transportation 911.94, up 20.10; utilities 227.31, up 0.86.    Bonds: Dow Jones 20 bonds 95.21, off 0.09.    Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 117.60, up 0.48; spot index 115.45, up 0.03. </TEXT></DOC>